Found by Cedric Duhalde this morning - I viewed it with Malia, Donna, and Joshua.  Closely paired with a single Black-bellied Plover on the upper sand about 100 yards south of the North parking lot.  Apparent first year bird judging by crisp feathers on breast, even wear and white edging.  Some yellow on cheek, behind eye and sides of neck.  Golden flecking down the length of the back but otherwise dull primaries and secondaries, heavily worn.  Bill heavier than American.  Primary extensions appear long and there was some discussion about American.  Long tibiae.

Continuing bird.  Standing alone.  Light grey breast and belly, black tail, grey wings, white supercilium, typical godwit bill.   -- (from NBB)  Hi Ken,  I guess I was the last person to report the Hudsonian Godwit on eBird, on September 24th. It took me a while to find it, so I thought I'd describe its general location in case you go up there this weekend.  I went up there on the morning of the 23rd, but immediately had to turn around and get back to SF to handle an urgent matter. On that morning there were six Pectoral Sandpipers together in the small holding pond to the north of the tracks. The Godwit was not visible from the railroad tracks and I didn't have time to look further.  I got back up there on the 24th around 9AM. The bird was NOT visible from the tracks nor the road (where construction is happening). Eventually I walked east on the tracks about 1000', past the ranch buildings. Then I cut through a break in the fence and walked south across the field. I'm not sure how cool that is, but there was a hunting regulation sign that didn't say anything against entering. The Godwit was visible after walking south a few hundred feet. It was in the farthest pond (the SE one of the pond complex) standing in a narrows area.

1st year bird in crisp juvenal plumage.   Found at about 9:45 am, as seen from the wood pedestrian bridge.  On the island with approximately 1,000 Elegant Terns - but more associated with a few Least Sandpipers and staying away from the terns.  Medium-sized shorebird, larger than pectoral, small than knot.   Had a very dumpy posture, not uncommon for juveniles, almost like a Green Heron when its head is down.   Bold, plain dark scapular feathers - which is the first thing I notice with Ruffs, with wide buffy fringes, all feathers appearing even aged.  Head and neck were dull buff color, no streaking on breast or belly.  Thin dark slightly-decurved "Dunlin-type" bill.  Dull green-yellow  "Willet-like" legs.  Head appears small for body, giving a hunched appearance when feeding.  Floppy rear wing feathers (extended tertials?) also diagnostic.

photos.Locality: Bodega Head - offshore species and the bluff ONLY
photos.Observation Details: Continuing. Life bird for me.  A lot like a Purple Sandpiper - a bit duller in color.  Associating with Surfbirds - similar color scheme, chevroned breast and flanks, tended to blend in with the sea rocks.   Smaller than a Black Turnstone, thinner and longer - bill is thin and decurved, yellow at the base (not always evident) - scaly pattern distinctive, dark secondaries with white fringe - one rufous (summer) scapular remaining.  Took about 20 minutes to find, I observed for about 30 minutes, spent most of the time with his head tucked in.  Very compatible with SURF and BLTU.

photos.Locality: Alviso Marina County Park (please use a specific pond hotspot where possible)
photos.Observation Details: The Little Stint was associating with a small group of Western Sandpipers and Dunlins, and not with Least Sandpipers.  It is about the size of a Least Sandpiper - considerably smaller than a Western.   The bill is short and slightly drooped with a distinct gape notch.   The legs are black and completely unwebbed (un-palmated).  They appear long relative to body size.  The most striking diagnostic feature are the rich rufous edges on the tertials that are coming in, along with one or two rufous scapulars.  The feathers have a black shaft and rufous edging.  Otherwise the bird was much greyer than the Western Sandpipers.    The scapulars have a solid blackish appearance.  The face has a "split" supercilium that I understand distinguishes it from the other stints - basically a forked eyebrow, that is visible in one of the photos.     In the hour that we were there the bird showed amazing fidelity to one particular spot in the middle of the pond, returning to it over and over to feed in water that was about one inch deep., and defending his space. We watched him get chased around a bit by an aggressive avocet.  Our view was from 125'.  There are 23 previous records in California - all but one between July and December.  There is just one spring record in May 1991 on the Salton Sea.

In addition to the numerous GRYE, an apparent LEYE popped into view for a couple of minutes alongside the two Baird's Sandpipers.  Noticably smaller than the Stilts and Killdeer, the bird had a rounded head and smaller straight bill that I associate with LEYE and a more delicate gait.  Though I did not see it in the same view as the nearby GRYE I'm confident this was a different and smaller bird.  Feedback welcome.

Continuing rarity.  Approximately the size of Lesser Yellowlegs but somewhat more slender.   Very pale white belly and head, medium gray wings with some mottling (from a distance) but not the intricate feather pattern of a yellowlegs sp.   Seems to indicate some alternate plumage wing feathers coming in.  I wonder if this bird is molting-in-migration or if it has been here all winter.    The bird was not associating with other tringa, and seemed to squabble a few times with American Avocet.   Bird has an interesting side to side sweeping motion when foraging in shallow water, reminiscent of an Avocet.  Bill is needle thin and straight.  Long thin gray legs.  I have previously observed them in India and Ghana.

photos.Observation Details: Continuing.  Refound by David Tomb at 2:40PM today on Hermit Rock.  I viewed it from 3:25-3:50PM, with about eight others.  Just poor quality iPhone shots through David's scope.   Small black and white auklet, smaller than PIGU and not really associating with any other birds.  Comparitively bulky red bill and fine single white line extending behind eye.  Moved about five times in the 25 minutes I viewed it, preferring the top half of the rock, and ultimately a small crevasse on the south (land facing) face of the rock.  Flew at about 3:50 in a bee-line out to the middle of the Golden Gate channel, presumably to feed as it was not being harassed at that moment.

Standing on the beach in the back of the flock. Well observed.  Adult in basic plumage.   Thin yellow bill, quite decurved (more than I remember).  Black stripe behind eye - gray wings with solid black tips.  Feet very black (I was kinda hoping for red).   I went back to my car to get the camera, but the bird took flight as I was returning.   Last seen circling repeatedly over the harbor, I expect it stayed in the area but didn't return to Deniston.   Distant flight shot.
